 Note especially that all the fuss is about tiny NEP probes. Nothing NASA is talking about funding is anywhere near as &quot;scary&quot; as the reactor the article talks about -or Orion!<br>
 I really like the comments about the reactor the people at LANL built &quot;the inactive core emits so little radiation that a person would have to hug it for 84 days to receive a dose of radiation as large as a typical chest X-ray&quot;.<br>
<br>
 As usual Gagnon's comments are off the mark.<br>
 All the concerns about launch accidents depend on an accident vaporizing the core, and spewing it all over. Patently wrong if it's designed correctly-even an _orbital_ re-entry wouldn'tbreak the case if it's done right. Who's saying that the 1970s Soviet military designs are the safest we could make?<br>
